If you have good credit and a big down payment, you will now have a higher mortgage payment because of the recent changes to conventional loans that happened in March. 

The banks have raised the loan level pricing adjustments (LLPA) so that buyers with good credit and big down payments pay higher fees to get a lower interest rate. 

But here is how you can get around having to pay these fees…

According to the Federal Housing Finance Agency (FHFA), if you are at or under 100% of the area median income, you can waive the extra fees. 

You can easily find out the area median income in your area by using the Fannie Mae AMI lookup tool. All you have to do is enter the address of the area you are searching, and it will show you the area median income. 

Certain areas require you to be under 120% of the area median income, like Los Angeles County, Orange County, and San Diego county, but majority of places want you to be 100% below. 

So that is how you avoid these new fees! If you want to know more, send me a message!

Don’t make this common homebuying mistake! 

I recently worked with a couple who wanted to buy a house. But because the wife recently bought a car, that added debt increased their debt-to-income ratio (DTI) significantly and now both the husband and wife do not qualify.

Many people don’t know this, but when you live in a community state, you are required to run your spouse’s credit, and any debts they have, will be added to your DTI. So even though the husband qualifies, because his wife just bought a new car, that debt is added to the DTI, which means the husband does not qualify anymore. 

Thankfully, I was able to find a solution for them. I noticed they had a 401k. So I suggested they take out a loan from their 401k to cover the balance of the car. So instead of making monthly payments towards their car, they would make monthly payments back into their 401k. When doing this, the monthly payment to the 401k loan, does not get added to your DTI. 

After removing that car payment from their DTI, they now qualify to buy! 

So if you’re married and you are about to buy a house, just know that if you live in a community state, you will have to run your spouse’s credit even if they are not added to the loan.

Here’s the one thing they don’t warn you about buying a home with a co-signer….

When it comes time for you to finally remove them from the loan, your home with get reassessed at the new home value. When this happens, that means you will now have to pay property taxes based on the new home value! Which means you will be paying way more than you were before. 

So how do you get around it? Here is what you can do…

As soon as escrow closes, remove your co-signer off the loan as soon as possible. That way when your home gets reassessed, the home value would remain the same as when you purchased it which would keep the property tax lower versus doing it years later.

[SAVE THIS POST!!] The one cheat sheet you NEED to save! ☝🏼 THE DTI CHEAT SHEET!

Your Debt-to-Income Ratio (DTI) is a way to measure an individual's ability to manage monthly payments and repay debt.

DTI is calculated by dividing total recurring monthly debt by the gross monthly income and it is expressed as a percentage.

EXAMPLE: 45% (front end)/ 55% (back end) = DTI

If a homeowner has a mortgage, the front end DTI ratio is usually calculated as housing expenses (such as mortgage payments, mortgage insurance, etc.) divided by gross income.

A back end DTI is usually the percentage of gross income going toward other types of debt such as credit cards or car loans.

Knowing how to calculate your DTI is one of the best ways to figure out your mortgage payment budget!

Homebuyers with big down payments in 2024 are gonna get hit hard! According to the updated FHFA guidelines, bigger down payments on conventional loans have an increased risk adjustment which means a higher interest rate. Here’s how you can potentially avoid this. Start by putting only 5% down. After 2-3 mortgage payments, call your lender and ask them to do a recast. That way you can put the remaining 15% down and they will recalculate the balance, drop the monthly payment AND keep the lower interest rate. PMI falls off after 20% of the original purchase price is paid off.
